      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">Career coaching cost — what the market looks like</h2>
      <p>Career coaching costs vary widely depending on the coach's background, the services included, and the engagement depth. Here is an honest overview of what the market looks like:</p>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li><strong>Resume-only services: $200–$800</strong> — A single document, no strategy, no coaching relationship</li>
        <li><strong>Session-based coaching: $150–$400 per hour</strong> — Useful for targeted needs, but no continuity between sessions</li>
        <li><strong>Package coaching (mid-level): $2,000–$5,000</strong> — Full engagement covering resume, LinkedIn, interview prep, and job search strategy</li>
        <li><strong>Executive coaching: $5,000–$15,000+</strong> — Senior and C-suite focused, often includes offer strategy and leadership positioning</li>
        <li><strong>Big coaching platforms: $3,000–$10,000</strong> — Typically matched to a coach you did not choose, varying quality</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="content-panel">
      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">The real ROI calculation</h2>
      <p>If you are targeting a role at $150K and your current compensation is $110K, you are leaving $40K per year on the table. Career coaching that helps you land that role in 60 days instead of 9 months is not an expense — it is a 7–10x return on the investment within the first year.</p>
      <p>The calculation is even more significant when you factor in negotiation outcomes. Askia's average client outcome in compensation-focused engagements is a $47K salary increase. A $4,000 coaching investment that produces a $47,000 compensation increase is a 10x return in year one — and compounds across every subsequent role and raise.</p>
      <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/is-career-coaching-worth-it/">Is career coaching worth it? →</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-tight">
  <div class="container two-col-grid">
    <div class="content-panel">
      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">What drives career coaching prices</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li><strong>Coach background:</strong> A coach with real hiring-side experience and industry depth commands higher rates — and produces better outcomes. Generic life coaches or career counselors charge less because they deliver less specialized value.</li>
        <li><strong>Scope of services:</strong> Resume-only vs. full-service (resume + LinkedIn + interview + offer strategy) represents a significant difference in both price and outcome</li>
        <li><strong>Target role level:</strong> Executive-level coaching is more expensive than mid-level coaching because the stakes are higher and the expertise required is deeper</li>
        <li><strong>Engagement length:</strong> 30-day intensive vs. 90-day comprehensive engagement differs in depth and cost</li>
        <li><strong>Coach availability:</strong> A coach working with 50 clients simultaneously cannot deliver what a coach working with 8–12 can</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="content-panel">
      <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow">What to watch out for when evaluating cost</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li><strong>Cheap resume services:</strong> A $99 resume rewrite from a template-based service is not career coaching. It is a formatting update.</li>
        <li><strong>Platform-matched coaches:</strong> Large coaching platforms charge coaching rates while paying coach contractors a fraction — the economics do not incentivize quality</li>
        <li><strong>No outcome data:</strong> If a coach cannot tell you what percentage of their clients land offers within a defined timeframe, that is a signal</li>
        <li><strong>Session-count pricing:</strong> Coaching priced by the session encourages dependency rather than outcomes — a good coach should have a defined endpoint</li>
        <li><strong>Upfront credentials without examples:</strong> Certifications matter less than proof. Ask for client outcomes, not certificates.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

